reasoning: This is a dynamic structural equation model (DSEM) for daily software debugging performance. The model has three layers: (1) A measurement model linking 26 observed browser-based indicators to 13 latent constructs via factor models with 2 indicators each, where one loading is fixed to 1 for identification. (2) A within-person temporal structural model with AR(1) dynamics for the 9 endogenous time-varying constructs, capturing day-to-day persistence. (3) A between-person structural model where 7 unobserved time-invariant exogenous constructs (developer experience, codebase complexity, etc.) influence endogenous constructs through fixed effects absorbed into person-level variation. Distribution choices reflect data types: NegativeBinomial for overdispersed browsing counts, Poisson for rare event counts, Bernoulli for binary indicators, OrderedLogistic for ordinal ratings, and Normal for continuous timestamps. Random intercepts for subjects on all 13 measured constructs capture stable between-person differences. The model is intentionally kept with intercept-only random effects (no random slopes) to maintain identifiability given the complexity of the structural model (40 causal paths, 9 AR parameters). Code Familiarity is modeled at daily resolution despite weekly granularity, with the expectation that its AR coefficient will be near 1 reflecting slow knowledge accumulation.
